@jbcrail I think this is partially resolved. We do now append at the specific offset, but I don't believe there is logic to catch an append that has already succeeded on the server but was retried (either due to a false failure or a transient network drop for the response). The result of the retry will be a `BadOffsetException` that looks like the below with a 400 response:

```{"RemoteException":{"exception":"BadOffsetException","message":"FsAppendStream failed with error 0x83090015 (Bad offset). [3f56efc4-7ab9-4908-9a12-028a0ca74e9f][2016-09-28T16:02:46.3881083-07:00]","javaClassName":"org.apache.hadoop.fs.adl.BadOffsetException"}}```

We should do an `Except` here if we get this error on a retry of an append and, if this is the error, mark the chunk that we were trying to append as succeeded and move on, instead of ultimately failing, which I believe is what will happen today, right?

